description.text: This is a tool holder that was created to keep all of the my 3D Printing tools organized on the workbench.  There are two versions - the first version has equal heights for each compartment, and the second version has tiered heights for each compartment.

MakerBot 2x with the following settings for ABS:
  • No support or rafts needed
  • 20% infill
  • 2 shell
  • 0.2mm layer

Because the difference between too lose and too tight can be often less than 0.2mm I decided to make a lot of variations with small 0.1mm differences between the sizes. It's 20 variations with a 0.1mm difference from the 3.0mm gap up to 5.0mm. That should fit on thin cables up to pretty thick. This solves the differences between printers, if mine would be overextruding and yours underextruding, your part could be lose while mine would fit perfectly, this way everybody can try and chose which one fits well. The print takes few minutes and takes very little filament so feel free to experiment. It was designed for 0.4 nozzles and 0.3 layer height (the separation for the magnet is 0.6mm, so 2 layers should be made there). But overall any common settings should do well (do not print it completely empty in the shell mode). But no support or anything should be needed.

The design is parametric and SolidWorks source is included. If needed a specific dimension can be made per request if somebody needs them.

The hole on the bottom is for 7mm x 3mm neodymium magnet, but it's a bit bigger so it will allow easily add magnets which are slightly off, or if your printer is not exact. This gives enough margin. These sized magnets are strong enough to keep the wires safely even in vertical orientation.

It was designed to stay on the cable all the time if you wish you can use glue, but for me, the friction and the exact sized clip does exactly that.

This is a canard that uses a printed body, fixed canard that is printed as part of the nose. This gives a 3 part fuselage and 5 joiners. I designed the canard/nose to be printed on my Anet A8 diagonally. Since the maiden flights I have added tapered wing tips.

The wing is made from foam in a stepped airfoil. I will include the shapes for it to be cut. I made the wing from MPF 6mm foam. Other foams could probably be substituted. it has a 40.5" span, 11 " center chord. The wingtips have a 4.25" chord, the wing tips are swept back 7.5". The elevons are 1.5x14". The CG is 3" behind root chord.

The wing has 1/4" wooden dowel leading edge spars (for toughness) and 3, 6mm carbon spars running spanwise at 1.75", 4" and 6" back from the center chord line. I used 12 gram metal gear servos at 7" out from the center line.

It has twin vertical stabilizers glued t the wing tips. I did not add any stiffeners to them. If you were to substitute for a a softer foam you may want to add a leading edge stiffener.

The motor is a 3010c Turnigy motor on a pedestal mount. 1300kv. It turns a thin 10x5 quad prop and is powered by a 1600/4s battery and 40amp speed control.

Maiden flight is here. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tcwfs8ura78

Watch carefully the launch, Hold by the front of the right wing and side arm release it with your left hand. This motor is powerful enough to injure or maim or kill.

Adding the optional fan

Since the modem has 2 USB outlets on the back I took an old 120 mm case fan, with blue led's for cool lighting effect, I had laying around and an old USB printer cable (any USB cable should do) and stripped the wires down on each piece. I attached the fan to the USB cable (on my cable the red and black wires from the USB matched the colors on my fan) and used some shrink tubing to seal them in place. I had the original screws from the fan but you could use anything such as double sided tape, super glue, wire, tie wrap or whatever you can fit into the 4.5 mm holes

Optionally you could try to find a pre-made 120 mm USB fan that runs off of 5 volts and buy one. Mine is a 12 volt fan that will run at 5 volts but it runs slower than normal. This turned out to be ideal as it provides just enough cooling and no wind noise.

While the fan with lights is not needed for this stand it is a nice touch while providing excellent cooling. I decided to go with a 120 mm fan since the 80 mm fan seemed, to me, a bit small for the surface area of the modem and ones I had didn't seem to play well with the lower 5 volts.

description.text:
I loved this holder, but I wanted something I could put my extra pieces in for storage. I added a small lip to the bottom of the holder, then a box that would go around it. To be glued on top is a "tablet" piece, it's just a lid, but since it has a design I separated it so that it would print properly without needing a bunch of supports or printing over the air (if it's upside down). Just needs to be glued in place.

This is the "Wide Road" version of the holder, which fits the roads as printed when I printed them. I've printed a few test pieces for this, but had a layer shift issue. I'm printing a new set now and hopefully will get some pictures up tomorrow (after I print all 3 parts).

It's designed for a Monoprice Maker Select v2, with a 200x200mm bed. You can only print 2 "parts" at a time, so the tablet has to be printed separately, which is fine because I want to try using cura's ironing feature on it, and I wanted the option to not have it on the rest.

This is my first published thing, so I apologize if I made any mistakes.

Update 12/12/2017: I wanted a good way to hold the pieces together that went with the magnet theme, so I edited the models to include a 3mmx1mm depression for a disk magnet (it's actually slightly larger to accommodate for my printer's tendency to print things smaller than it should).

I don't really like how it works on the box. I wanted a little tolerance for fit, so the box is 1mm thinner than the lip on the holder. That makes the magnet offset, and makes it so that it won't really print the inner gap. It's an aesthetics thing, shouldn't affect functionality once you glue the magnet in place, but I may edit it and make it look better, just wanted to put this up for anyone wanting to print it

Update 2 for 12/12/2017: Did some thinking and redesigned with a slightly larger lip and slightly wider walls to accommodate for the magnet. Also designed that pin that goes into it; the pin existed in the thin road variant, but not the wide road that I've remixed, but it was just slightly too big. I scaled it down a bit. When my magnets come in, I'll take some photos of them installed (assuming they fit properly of course)

description.text:
I was looking for a box to put a small vtx in to use on the bench that would keep all the wires together- came across the Tevo mosfet box- Thank you Razzerback for the initial design- and used that as a starting point. I raised the standoffs in the interior corners and removed the dimples for the mosfet board holes. Then I designed a new bed to act as a shelf- so the wires can go underneath and the vtx can sit on top and be zip tied to it with the shelf is easily removable. Then modified the lid to have a vertical wall that a camera can be mounted to with holes for wires to go back down into the box. Planning on using an Eachine mini vtx, so the antenna will just stick out the non fan end. The enclosure has room for a slip in 30mm fan at one end to keep everything cool. Going to use a bec and power it from a 2s lipo.

I was working on setting up micro minimosds for fpv flying wings, and the whole process from camera focusing to programming the osd was a pain in the but trying to do inside the model. and thought it would be nice to have a bench vtx that I could work on that had everything out in the open, but was compact and a single unit that I could easily hook stuff up to.

Will upload pics when it is done.

12.11.17... so my heater element burned out 99% of the way through printing the box, but it looks good- the shelf needs to be a few mm wider and as mentioned earlier 3mm thick instead of 5... and I expect I will want to make a few more tweaks once all the guts come in the mail this week- perhaps a tray to hold a 2s lipo - i plan on running the connector out the round hole on the side of the box, so perhaps some sort of tray there. I want the box to sit flat on a surface but be able to pick it up when powered and move it around.

12.15.17... heater element comes today, but got fan yesterday and made a couple of changes to the box- moved the hole in the side down and made it bigger so that I can get the wire to fit through with a jst connector on it, I made the tabs that hold the fan in a little longer, and added 2 channels at the bottom of the fan space for the wire to pass through. also added some additional holes on that face of the box- I figure I will use a velcro strap to hold the battery on on that side. Also closed in the open side on the bed, but left that gap a little bigger for wires to pass through.

12.18.2017- so printed out the last version and realized a couple of things.
1) The hole in the side of the box wasn't big enough for the jst connector to fit through.
2) The design for the lid was a little too elaborate and not as sturdy as I wanted. Turns out that all I needed was a 3mm hole in the lid for a screw to hold down a runcam mount, so I have simplifed the lid to have just the cable passthroughs and that hole.

The picture of the actual thing made is of the next to the last design, It works well enough for me, but I took the learnings from putting it together detailed above and made the mods to end up with the final design.

Ever open a 2 liter bottle of soda only to find it went flat:(. Well not anymore, my mission was to make the world a bubblier place:) My thing will allow one to pump air into a soda bottle to increase pressure so you lose less CO2 or better know as bubble\'s. Also could be used as a scientific tool as a pressurization/depressurization chamber. This is a prototype and may need tweaking if it doesn't work i know i can get it to by tweaking and maybe use of 1 o-ring.

ok a few instructions are needed item\'s needed other then a 3D printer = any soda bottle cap, a 3/4\" drill, and 1 other drill size between 1/4\" to 1/8\" should do fine, and a piece of balloon \"other materials could work as long as it can plug a hole air tight when under pressure\" also need Glue exp \"superglue\" Steps 1. take soda bottle cap and 3/4\" drill carefully drill the very \"center\" trying not to destroy the outer rim of its seal plate.

  • take the print \"3D model\" of (Bottle_Cap_Chamber_with_out_hole.stl) and the smaller drill between 1/4\" and 1/8\" and drill the hole in the center

  • after that take (Bottle_Cap_Chamber_with_out_hole.stl) with the new hole you have drilled... cut a circular piece of \"balloon\" so that it can fit over the hole on the out side with extra slack.
  • READ CARFULLY then take the piece of balloon and glue it to the outside surface over hole (important it must be on the outside surface, that way the pressure in bottle forms the seal/ 1 way valve). Make shore you don\'t glue it completely. glue it so the balloon piece seats nicely over the hole but also will allow air to flow from inside to outside surface. \"glue it in 4 corner spots\" allow to dry.. that\'s the best i could explain it comment me if you don\'t get this part
    • 4.then take that peace and put it into the soda bottle cap, the 3/4 hole you drilled, you should see that there\'s a lip that stops it from going all the way threw and glue that together completely making it air tight 5.Now take the print (bottle_cappiston.stl) and here\'s how to operate the pump effectively put the piston peace into the new bottle cap you made. you will see the piston part has a small hole that leads all the way down. As you push down on the piston cover the hole with your thumb, finger, or palms pushing air into the bottle, then let go of the hole when you lift piston up allowing air to enter the chamber and repeat. Also you will only need 1 piston peace that\'s all you will need to pump up multiple caps because you can completely remove the piston and go to another bottle with the special cap :) \"still need to make the extra caps for more bottles just don\'t need to keep making the piston piece\" Enjoy a more bubblier world

title: CO2 Laser Head Mount for 30mm Mirror & 20mm Focus Lens

description.text:
This is intended to go along with the 30mm mirrors cut from hard disk platters.  If you want to use real mirrors, you can do that too.  Just keep in mind that the optimal distance from the mirror to the mount block should be around 2mm.  
This design has been tested on a 100 Watt CO2 Reci Laser tube, with no major problems.  The laser was well aligned beforehand.  YMMV.  I would recommend this for 40 Watt CO2 laser tubes, or lower, as the mirrors tend to get very hot on the larger lasers.  Gluing a heat sink back there might help.  
I'll be some images with a FLIR to see if the mirrors deform at all during lasing.  
All hardware is 3mm.  The three shoulder screws are meant to hold an elastic band or o-ring to act as the spring for the mirror angle adjust.  Thumb screws are 12mm in length.  Regular screws will do in their place.  
The nozzle tube v3 has a slight taper on the end to make it slip on easier.  Also the neck around where the lens goes has been strengthened.

My X-axis stepper motor likes to run hot after a while (~70 Celsius) and the temperature is way above safe threshold (you cannot keep touching it for longer than few seconds), so I've decided to take care of that issue and the other one with loose stepper motor cables.

What you need:
1) Aluminium radiator 43 x 40 x 11 mm - I've got mine from some old, passively cooled GPU card. You can always narrow radiator slot down in 3D_Stepper_Bottom_Alternative to fit smaller radiator.
2) Fan 40 x 40 x 10 mm - Mine is Sunon 12V.
3) 2x M3 25mm Allan screws,
4) 2x M3 washers,
5) Thermal Tape, 0.5-1 mm thick to put on the radiator, where it will have contact with stepper motor.

description.text: Buy some NEO already.

Hi all,

Here is my latest creation an AI powered cat feeder :)

Inside is a 3D printed mechanism with an auger allowing to push out the pellets.
a servo rotates gears and the auger which is into a PVC pipe.

Cat is detected with a neural network running on an old android phone.
The camera runs in real time and performs cat face detection

When the cat is detected then the auger can run and feeds the cat (only twice a day)

And the phone streams your cat over internet so you can see it eating !

More details here :
https://www.b4x.com/android/forum/threads/jg-ecatfeeder.87088/#post-551293

[edit] It was Xmas for my cat...

A drawback of previous design was that I was always feeding the cat with the same amount of food. So sometimes too much when the cat wasn't hungry...

I decided to mod a little my cafeeder to add a balance to weight the food.
A simple load cell + a Hx711 interface circuit, and now :

  • always the same quantity of food into the plate
  • a real time monitoring of the weight which allows to detect the cat "eating" and to post a notification for the camera streaming
  • a detection of empty tank plus a notification to alarm you on your phone

print it

All is printed in PLA excepted the auger and the gears which are in ABS

Auger is cut horizontally printed and then acetone glued
the big gear is acetone glued to the auger and screwed to it

A pvc pipe is inserted in the main frame and a slot is cut to allow pelets to fall

hardware

The front face is equiped with a PIR sensor and an android smartphone (screen is dead but the camera works !)

software

Most of the time everything sleeps : NO power when in sleep mode

  • The PIR sensor wakes up the ESP8266
  • if it's time (NTP connection) to feed the cat, then the ESP8266 sends a firebase notification
  • the smartphone is registered to this notification. It wakes up
  • a face cat detection is launched (real time OpenCV lib) : my cat on the picture :-)
  • if it is a cat then the smartphone which has connected to the ESP8266 via UDP, sends a feed notification
  • the ESP8266 launches the auger rotation

  • and meanwhile the smartphone streams a video of your beloved cat over internet !

  • then smartphone and ESP8266 go back into deep sleep mode !

title: Interior and accessories for the VW Bus

description.text:
Having seen the bus that ChaosCoreTech designed i just had to print one for a friend. But i wanted it to be more, i wanted it to be lighted and have an interior.

With this remix you get:

  • The body with a hole for a 9V battery, the rest of the body is original and unaltered.
  • The roof file, hollowed out so that potential light could also come out of the roof windows. (if you decide to light your model)
  • Battery holder box (glue in place over the hole (or if you want you can merge the 2 files in a program such as meshmixer if you want it to be already attached to the main body)
  • Battery cover (i drilled out the 2 hole in the bottom of the body and then glued 2 M3 nuts on the inside to hold 2 m3 bolts)
  • Dashboard (you can print it without supports if you want, but i did use supports just for the part that hols the steering wheel, just glue to the inside of the front)
  • Steering wheel ( the hole can be too small on some printers, i suggest to use a 2mm drill bit and make the hole a little larger, you can then use a piece of filament as the steering bar and glue the steering wheel to the dashboard.)
  • Mirrors (small cirkels, you will need to print 2, and you can again use a small piece of filament and bent it with pliers into the correct shape and glue them to the model body, see pictures)
  • Front seats (consists of a false bottom plate with the front 2 seats and the first bench, designed to hide wires in the bottom if you light your model)
  • Back seats (also the false bottom plate with the second bench)

The reason for the seating so be divided into 2 files, is that you will need two separate pieces when installing them into the body. The body is tapered and thus a full plate would not pass though the roof opening. Also you will need to add something for support in the middle, i suggest the battery box, even if you don't want to light the model, you could use the box as an anker point for the false floor.

Don't forget the get the original thing for the missing files like the wheels and pins. or the body if you don't want to light it.

title: MP Select Mini 50mm blower fan side panel with guard

description.text:
The first thing I noticed when I got my Monoprice Select Mini, is that it got a bit hot inside during long prints, and it doesn't have any fans inside! I wasn't quite happy with any of the other side panel mods, and the only fan I had on hand was a 50x15mm blower, so I made my own. These fans can be had pretty cheaply (paid about $1.25 for mine) and they move a good amount of air. Search 50mm 12v blower, and you should get a ton of results for this exact fan.

This was designed to direct air right at the hot parts of the board, and the heat-sinks on my controller board barely get above room temperature now.

The fan clips on without the need for any fasteners.

Bonus! Included fan guard, designed to maximize airflow. Attach with double-stick tape.

description.text:
I designed this canopy at the request of a local FPV pilot. It is intended to be printed with a flexible filament (see print settings for more info). The canopy is designed for an X style racing frame. and should work regardless of prop size (4" or 5"). It should work on just about any frame. This canopy comes in two parts:

Part 1: pod_base.stl - this base will fit over a single stack FC/PDB/ESC. It has notches cut out of the corners so wires can fit, and an ESC plug can route out the back.

Part 2: pod_camera.stl - this will fit a runcam swift or similar size camera. Since the sides are flexible, it should accommodate a fairly wide range of cameras. The runcam swift is approximately 24x24mm square, so anything around that size (give or take a few mm) should work. The canopy is also designed to hold an Eachine VTX03. It should fit pretty snug in place and still provide access to press the button.

Instructions:

  1. Mount your PDB up with a small spacer. Aim for about 16mm in total height you should be fine. You can go smaller or larger, but the pod base may not fit as well. When mounting your PDB, I recommend using 25mm m3 screws. That length should give you enough room for the base and the canopy, with a little room on top for nylocks/lock nuts.

  2. Make sure you solder all the wires you are going to need (ESC, Battery Connector, Motors, Receiver, Video Transmitter, Camera).

  3. Slide the canopy over the screws. Tuck in all your wires and anything else (such as your radio receiver) so it stays under the canopy. Route the wires for the video transmitter and fpv camera, as well as anything else you might be putting in the canopy.

  4. I recommend putting some glue on the Eachine vtx03 where the antenna is, before placing it in the canopy. This will help ensure it stays on. The vtx03 should stay seated, but you may also want to glue it in place with some hot glue or Shoegoo.

  5. Screw the FPV camera in from the sides. Adjust the angle. You should be able to angle it up to 60" or so with the cut out. If the screws are a bit loose, you may be able to use some spacers to help.

  6. Place the canopy on top of the base. The screws should line up. Secure the canopy with m3 lock nuts.

Enjoy!

Use a flexible filament. I recommend Sainsmart TPU. I was able to print both the base and canopy fine with no supports.

You will need to flip the base over in your slicer (rotate 180).

Print the canopy right side up. Without supports, the inside under the top it might look a little droopy as the printer tries to bridge. However, it should look fine on the outside and it should hold up fine to crashes. The sides are quite thin, but most of the impact in a crash is probably going to be from the top.
